The ratio of the number of Ti4+ to Ti3+ ions in titanium oxide was calculated based on surface analysis by XPS, using the relative sensitivity factor method. The results of the quantitative elemental analysis showed that the calculation equation can be described as follows [19]:

                                 NTi2p(Ti
                                    4+
                                    ): NTi2p(Ti
                                    3+
                                    )=A Ti2p(Ti
                                    4+
                                    )/S Ti2p(Ti
                                    4+
                                    ): A Ti2p(Ti
                                    3+
                                    )/S Ti2p(Ti
                                    3+
                                    )


                           where A is the peak area of the element and S is the element sensitivity factor. Since the same titanium element on one sample surface has the same sensitivity, the calculation equation can be simplified to the following equation [19]:

                                 NTi2p(Ti
                                    4+
                                    ): NTi2p(Ti
                                    3+
                                    )=A Ti2p(Ti
                                    4+
                                    ): A Ti2p(Ti
                                    3+
                                    )

As shown in Fig. 14
                           , the pH has a significant effect on the final coated product. When the pH of the solution was greater than 5.0 or less than 4.0, the black titanium oxide particles on the surface of kieselguhr were distributed unevenly and agglomerated, as shown in Fig. 14(a) and (b). Additionally, the ΔL* of the product had a positive value (Table 8
                           ) indicating its blackness was lower than that of the standard sample. This probably happens because when the pH value exactly corresponded to the precipitation pH value of Ti3+ within the pH range of 4.0–4.5, the submicron titanium oxides TiO2-x were very evenly coated on the surface of kieselguhr@TiO2 with an average particle diameter within 110–140 nm, and as a result the coating layer was very compacted and smooth, as shown in Fig. 14(c). When the pH was higher, the precipitation of Ti3+ occurred quickly, leading the TiO2-x coating layer to become uniformly coated, and agglomeration was observed, the density and smoothness of the coating layer was inadequate. As shown in Table 8, the ΔL* of the product is a negative value and the product had the highest blackness at pH 4.5.
